erate risks for humanitarians, but also mean that humanitarians themselves can put populations in need at risk.The book explores new humanitarian spaces and practices such as the humanitarian drone airspace, wearable innovation challenges and ethics in global disaster innovation labs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBig dataxSocial aspects. 0aHumanitarian assistancexData processing. 0aHumanitarian assistancexTechnological innovations. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Disasters & Disaster Relief.2bisacsh  aHumanitarianism.  acybersecurity.  adigital body.  adigital transformation.  adisaster response.  adrone airspace.  ahumanitarian innovation labs.  ahumanitarian technology ethics.  ainformation and communications technology.  awearables.1 aSandvik, Kristin Bergtora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152616583140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526165831423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526165831/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles